<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ops-churn-basics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>growth-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Measure churn baseline with three metrics: customer churn, MRR churn, NRR. Track voluntary and involuntary churn separately. Use health scores to identify at-risk customers before they cancel.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>churn</tag>
      <tag>retention</tag>
      <tag>saas-metrics</tag>
      <tag>measurement</tag>
      <tag>health-score</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Churn Basics</title>
    <summary>Churn measurement is the prerequisite for retention intervention. Three metrics reported together: customer churn rate, MRR churn rate, Net Revenue Retention (NRR). Voluntary and involuntary churn tracked separately. Health score provides leading indicators before cancel.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>At 5% monthly churn, half of customers leave every year. Reducing from 5% to 3% roughly doubles LTV. But acting on churn requires knowing when it happens (cohort timing), why it happens (exit survey), and who is at risk (health score). Without measurement and segmentation, prevention work is guesswork. This methodology provides the measurement and segmentation layer; ops-churn-prevention covers interventions.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Subscription/usage-based business needing a baseline churn rate before prevention work.</item>
        <item>Quarterly review or board prep requiring customer churn, MRR churn, NRR, and segment breakdowns.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing whether retention pain is acquisition-mix, new-cohort onboarding, or aging-cohort decay.</item>
        <item>Precursor to ops-churn-prevention and cohort-basics.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-off transactional businesses without subscriptions — measure repeat-purchase rate instead.</item>
        <item>Free B2C with no revenue — focus on retention curves directly.</item>
        <item>Pre-revenue products — churn is meaningless until cohort sizes stabilize.</item>
        <item>Annual-only contracts with fewer than 2 renewal cycles — sample too small for a stable rate.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Churn Metric Definitions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define churn once in writing with cancel-date semantics and grace-period rules; pin that definition in every dashboard description.</statement>
        <rationale>Ambiguity in "churn date" (cancel event vs end-of-paid-period vs failed-payment threshold) produces different numbers in different tools and makes cross-team reporting meaningless.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always report voluntary and involuntary churn separately.</statement>
        <rationale>Involuntary churn (failed payments) is recoverable with dunning and smart retries — it has different root causes and different fixes than voluntary cancellation. Lumping them hides a fixable revenue leak.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Report customer churn alongside NRR; never report NRR alone in an expansion-led business.</statement>
        <rationale>NRR above 100% can mask high logo churn when expansion MRR from surviving accounts exceeds lost MRR from churned accounts. SaaS investors look at NRR >= 110% (good) and >= 120% (great) but always alongside logo churn.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Customer churn rate = customers lost this month / customers at start of month</item>
        <item>MRR churn rate = lost MRR this month / MRR at start of month</item>
        <item>Net Revenue Retention = (start MRR + expansion MRR - churned MRR) / start MRR</item>
        <item>Annual churn from monthly: 1 - (1 - monthly_rate)^12 (non-linear — do not linearly extrapolate)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Benchmarks">
      <list>
        <item>Consumer SaaS: 5-7% monthly, 45-60% annual</item>
        <item>SMB SaaS: 3-5% monthly, 30-45% annual</item>
        <item>Mid-market: 1-2% monthly, 10-20% annual</item>
        <item>Enterprise: below 1% monthly, below 10% annual</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Health Score Model">
      <rule>
        <statement>Backtest health-score thresholds against last 90 days of actual churn before trusting the alerts.</statement>
        <rationale>Health scores derived from short windows drift fast after product changes. An unvalidated score will fire false alerts and train teams to ignore it. Retro-fit threshold values against known churners before deploying to CS teams.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Composite health score combining four signals, each 0-25 points:</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Health Score = (
  login_frequency_score  (0-25) +
  feature_usage_score    (0-25) +
  support_sentiment      (0-25) +
  account_age_score      (0-25)
) / 100

Thresholds (validate against actual churn):
  < 40  = At-risk → CS outreach
  40-70 = Needs attention → automated nudge
  > 70  = Healthy]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Churn Reasons">
      <list>
        <item>Not using product: 25-30% of churn, preventable with activation fix</item>
        <item>Not seeing value: 20-25%, preventable with onboarding or success team</item>
        <item>Switched to competitor: 15-20%, partially preventable</item>
        <item>Budget/price: 15-20%, partially preventable with pricing tiers</item>
        <item>Business closed: 5-10%, not preventable</item>
        <item>Bad support experience: 5-10%, preventable</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Only measuring churn rate without leading indicators.</description>
        <reason>Churn rate is a lagging metric — the customer has already left. Leading indicators (login frequency drop, feature usage reduction, support frustration) provide a 2-4 week window for intervention.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Annualizing monthly churn by multiplying by 12.</description>
        <reason>Monthly churn compounds non-linearly. At 5% monthly, annual churn is 46%, not 60%. Linear extrapolation overstates the problem and distorts forecasts.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running health-score alerts without backtesting thresholds.</description>
        <reason>Unvalidated thresholds produce high false-positive rates. CS teams start ignoring alerts within weeks, making the entire system useless.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Churn Analysis Process">
      <section name="Define Churn">
        <list>
          <item>Define customer churn with explicit cancel-date and grace-period rules</item>
          <item>Define user churn separately if product has free tier (no login in X days)</item>
          <item>Choose measurement period (monthly is standard for SaaS)</item>
          <item>Separate voluntary from involuntary (failed payment) churn in schema</item>
          <item>Document definitions in every dashboard description</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Measure Current Churn">
        <list>
          <item>Calculate monthly customer churn rate and MRR churn rate</item>
          <item>Calculate NRR (start + expansion - churn) / start</item>
          <item>Report voluntary and involuntary churn separately</item>
          <item>Calculate cohort-specific churn (signup quarter, plan, channel)</item>
          <item>Benchmark vs industry standards for your segment</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Analyze Patterns and Root Causes">
        <list>
          <item>Identify when users churn: day 1, week 2, month 3, year-1 renewal</item>
          <item>Compare churned vs retained user behavior (login frequency, feature usage)</item>
          <item>Survey every churner with 6 fixed-taxonomy reasons; free text as supplemental only</item>
          <item>Interview high-value churners (top 20% by MRR)</item>
          <item>Analyze support ticket patterns in last 30 days before cancel</item>
          <item>Categorize churn reasons; identify top 2-3 preventable categories</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Segmentation">
        <list>
          <item>Segment churn by plan tier, signup channel, signup cohort quarter</item>
          <item>Segment by usage level: power users, casual users, at-risk</item>
          <item>Identify geography-specific churn patterns</item>
          <item>Separate involuntary churn for dunning/recovery analysis</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Health Score Setup">
        <list>
          <item>Define 4-6 behavioral signals as health score inputs</item>
          <item>Backtest thresholds against last 90 days of actual churn data</item>
          <item>Set alert thresholds for CS outreach (score below 40)</item>
          <item>Recalibrate health score thresholds quarterly</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Dashboarding and Monitoring">
        <list>
          <item>Create monthly churn dashboard: customer churn, MRR churn, NRR, voluntary/involuntary split</item>
          <item>Add cohort churn view segmented by plan, channel, quarter</item>
          <item>Set up alerts for churn rate exceeding threshold</item>
          <item>Generate weekly at-risk account list from health score</item>
          <item>Track churn reasons over time to measure intervention impact</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Integration">
      <p>Use Claude subagents to (1) compute the canonical churn metrics from raw billing + activity data, (2) segment churn by reason / cohort / plan / channel, (3) build and maintain a health-score model, and (4) produce a written narrative. The agent stays read-only against the warehouse and outputs into BI-friendly artifacts (SQL views, dbt models, dashboards). Never let it modify billing or downgrade users.</p>
      <section name="Recommended Subagents">
        <list>
          <item>data-analyst (sonnet) — SQL for churn definitions, segment cuts, NRR.</item>
          <item>growth-marketer (sonnet) — interpret segments, propose follow-ups (link to ops-churn-prevention).</item>
          <item>cs-ops (sonnet) — define health-score thresholds, at-risk lists for CSMs.</item>
          <item>bi-engineer (sonnet) — promote queries into dbt models with tests.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Prompt Pattern">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Input: schema (subscriptions, invoices, events) + window (last 12 full months)
Goal: compute monthly customer-churn, MRR-churn, expansion-MRR, NRR
      segmented by (plan, signup_channel, signup_cohort_quarter)
Output: 1) read-only SQL (no DDL), 2) results table,
        3) 3 hypotheses ranked by ICE (impact, confidence, ease)
Constraint: voluntary and involuntary churn reported separately]]></code>
      </section>
      <section name="CLI Tools">
        <list>
          <item>stripe CLI — Pull subscription + invoice events for churn defs (brew install stripe/stripe-cli/stripe)</item>
          <item>recurly / chargebee API — Subscription state + cancel reasons (https://docs.recurly.com / https://apidocs.chargebee.com)</item>
          <item>dbt-core — Build canonical churn / NRR models (pip install dbt-core)</item>
          <item>metabase / mode API — Embed/auto-refresh churn dashboards (https://www.metabase.com/docs/latest/api-documentation)</item>
          <item>posthog CLI — Activity events feeding health score (npm i -g posthog-node)</item>
          <item>bq (BigQuery) — Run + schedule churn jobs (gcloud components install bq)</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Services and Apps">
        <list>
          <item>Stripe Billing (SaaS) — Full API. Source of truth for subscription state.</item>
          <item>Chargebee (SaaS) — REST API. Subscription lifecycle, cancel reasons.</item>
          <item>Recurly (SaaS) — REST API. Mid-market subscription billing.</item>
          <item>ProfitWell / Paddle Retain (SaaS) — REST API. Free tier for retention metrics, recovery tooling.</item>
          <item>Vitally / Totango / Gainsight (SaaS) — REST API. Health scoring, CS playbooks.</item>
          <item>ChartMogul (SaaS) — REST API. Subscription analytics; canonical churn / NRR.</item>
          <item>Baremetrics (SaaS) — REST API. Churn dashboards, recovery.</item>
          <item>Mixpanel / Amplitude (SaaS) — REST API. Behavioral signals into health score.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="Best Practices">
        <list>
          <item>Define churn once, in writing, with cancel-date semantics and grace-period rules — and pin that definition in every dashboard description.</item>
          <item>Always report voluntary and involuntary churn separately; involuntary is recoverable with dunning + smart-retries.</item>
          <item>Pair customer churn with NRR; SaaS investors look at NRR >= 110% (good) and >= 120% (great) for product-led growth.</item>
          <item>Cohort-segment every reported number (signup quarter, plan, channel) — global numbers hide stage-specific problems.</item>
          <item>Run an exit survey on every cancel event with &lt;=6 reasons; free-text only as supplemental.</item>
          <item>Health-score thresholds should be backtested: retro-fit against last 90 days of actual churn before trusting the alerts.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
        <list>
          <item>Free-text "cancel reason" classification with LLMs hallucinates categories; force a fixed taxonomy in the prompt and require N/A when unclear.</item>
          <item>Agents will mix MRR churn and customer churn in the same sentence. Demand explicit metric names per number.</item>
          <item>Health-score "model" suggestions from LLMs are usually unweighted sums; do not adopt without backtesting against actual churn.</item>
          <item>"Reduce churn by X%" projections in agent output should be flagged as hypotheses, not forecasts — require an A/B-test plan before stating expected lift.</item>
          <item>Date-window bugs: the agent must pin `as_of` and "month boundary in customer timezone vs UTC" — small shifts produce large reported deltas.</item>
          <item>Annualized churn formulas are non-linear; agents that linearly extrapolate quarterly to annual will be wrong.</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/monthly-churn.sql" purpose="Voluntary vs involuntary customer + MRR churn SQL (warehouse-native)"/>
      <template path="templates/churn-report.md" purpose="Monthly churn analysis dashboard template"/>
    </templates>
